Q FEVER - NETHERLANDS (03): UPDATE
***********************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

[1]
Date: Wed 6 Jan 2010
Source: Dutch Ministry of Agriculture press release [trans. by
communicator, abridged, edited]
<http://www.minlnv.nl/portal/page?_pageid=116,1640333&_dad=portal&_schema=PORTAL&p_news_item_id=24977>


6 Jan 2010 Ministries update
-----------------------------
Ministers Verburg (LNV/Agriculture) and Klink (VWS/Public Health)
have sent a letter to Parliament today [6 Jan 2010] about the
activities regarding Q-fever control. This press release covers the
main points included in that letter, as well as information on
modifications for bulk milk monitoring and other current issues
presented hereunder.

1. Update on the cullings
-------------------------
At the moment, 61 farms have been declared contaminated, based on
bulk milk testing results. We expect to have the results of the
current [biweekly] bulk milk tests next week. At 24 contaminated
farms, animals have been examined for pregnancy to distinguish the
pregnant and not-pregnant. Subsequently, all pregnant animals on
these farms have been valued. So far, a total of 8724 animals on 21
farms have been culled.

2. Small-scale farms and children's/petting farms
-----------------------------------------
Minister Klink has asked the experts' group [see comment] to advise
him about the health risks of Q-fever at children's farms, farms with
less than 50 animals and farms with a public function [e.g. nursing
homes etc.]. According to the experts, no extra measures need to be
taken regarding this cluster of farms.

The experts believe that direct contact with sheep and goats is not a
risk factor. Recent research data also show that Q-fever bacteria are
hardly ever found at children's farms. There are no indications that
children's farms and other small-scale farms have a higher health
risk to the public.

The experts advised, however, to pay special attention to hygiene
measures. Therefore, a hygiene protocol will be made for the
small-scale sheep and goat farms. As soon as this protocol is
available, it will be published on the website page "Hobbydierhouders
en dierhouders met een publieke functie" (Hobby animal holders and
animal keepers with a public function).

Notification to the VWA (Food Safety Authority) in case of an
abnormal number of abortions, has long been obligatory for hobby
animal holders and animal keepers with a public function (like
children's farms). After notification, the VWA used to investigate
the farm as a standard procedure; until recently, such holdings were
tested for _Brucella melitensis_ bacteria (causing Brucellosis).
Currently, such notifications will be followed also by testing for
the Q-fever bacteria (_Coxiella burnetii_).

3. Mutton sheep farms
---------------------
The experts' group led by the RIVM (National Institute for Public
Health and Environment) has already advised on 24 Jul 2009 that
mutton-type sheep farms pose no risk within the Q-fever epidemic.
However, large numbers of ewes are soon to start lambing in the huge
straw-bedding stables at the large-scale mutton-type sheep farms.
Therefore, it has been decided that for these large-scale farms, the
same precautionary policy will be applied as for small-scale farms
with less than 50 ruminants. Hence, the advice addressing the hygiene
protocol for small-scale farms and children's farms will be also
applied in the mutton producing farms.

4. Judicial verdict
-------------------
On 4 Jan 2010, the judge of the Board of Appeal for Commerce and
Industry has issued a sentence on account of the request from a goat
keeper to spare from culling the animals which were kept in a
different location than the holding found infected, although both
groups of animals were registered under the same company number as
the infected farm. The request from this goat keeper has been denied.
According to the judge, both locations are connected units of one
company, as goats have been taken from one location to the other. At
the location which, according to the goat keeper, was Q-fever free,
offspring of goats from the infected holding are kept. The latter was
found infected by means of the bulk milk tests. Besides, the goats on
the Q-fever "free" location have not all been vaccinated on time. The
full text of the judge's sentence (verdict No BK8183 is available at
<http://www.rechtspraak.nl/Gerechten/CBb/Actualiteiten/Doden+van+drachtige+en+mannelijke+geiten+op+beide+locat!

ies+toegestaan.htm>.

