[Thanks to Christine Bijl, as well as to Mary Marshall and Sabine
Zentis for their share in obtaining the above information.

The letter VDC 09.2949/CPM of the Agriculture Minister to the Dutch
Parliament, dated 6 Jan 2010, is accompanied by 2 letters (23 Dec
2009, 5 Jan 2010), addressed to both ministries by Prof Roel
Coutinho, Director of the Centre for Infectious Disease Control of
the RIVM [National Dutch Institute for Public Health and the
Environment]. The 2 letters include the detailed replies to new
queries from the 2 Ministries requesting scientific advice concerning
issues raised during the epidemic. The RIVM response is based upon
consultations of experts, principally veterinarians, physicians and
microbiologists. The consultations are chaired by Prof Coutinho, and
the secretary of the body is Dr Jim van Steenbergen, RIVM. The lists
of the experts involved are attached to each advisory response.
Earlier meetings of the experts group were conducted on 11 and 30 Nov
2009, similarly chaired by Prof Coutinho. Several written advices,
agreed to by the experts, have already been attached to Ministers'
letters to the Parliament (e.g. 16 Dec 2009). All interested in the
various aspects (e.g. scientific-professional, political, social,
economic etc.) of coordinated control of emerging or re-emerging
zoonotic diseases are certainly following with great interest the
evolvement and management of the Dutch Q fever epidemic. - Mod.AS]

******
[2]
Date: Thu 7 Jan 2010 (accessed)
Source: Applied & Environmental Microbiology Vol. 75, No. 2, 2009, pp
428-433 [edited]
<http://aem.asm.org/cgi/reprint/75/2/428.pdf>


_Coxiella burnetii_ Shedding Routes and Antibody Response after
Outbreaks of Q Fever-Induced Abortion in Dairy Goat Herds
---------------------------------
Abstract
Q fever is a zoonosis caused by _Coxiella burnetii_, a bacterium
largely carried by ruminants and shed into milk, vaginal mucus, and
feces. The main potential hazard to humans and animals is due to
shedding of bacteria that can then persist in the environment and be
aerosolized. The purpose of this study was to evaluate shedding after
an outbreak of Q fever abortion in goat herds and to assess the
relationship with the occurrence of abortions and antibody responses.
Aborting and nonaborting goats were monitored by PCR for _C.
burnetii_ shedding 15 and 30 days after the abortion episodes. PCR
analysis of all samples showed that 70 percent (n 50) of the aborting
and 53 percent (n 70) of the non-aborting goats were positive. _C.
burnetii_ was shed into vaginal mucus, feces, and milk of 44, 21, and
38 percent, respectively, of goats that aborted and 27, 20, and 31
percent, respectively, of goats that delivered normally. Statistical
comparison of these shedding results did not reveal any difference
between these 2 groups. PCR results obtained for the vaginal and
fecal routes were concordant in 81 percent of cases, whereas those
for milk correlated with only 49 percent of cases with either vaginal
or fecal shedding status. Serological analysis, using enzyme-linked
immunosorbent assay (ELISA), indirect immunofluorescence assay (IFA),
and complement fixation tests showed that at least 24 percent of the
seronegative goats shed bacteria. Positive vaginal and fecal
shedding, unlike positive milk shedding, was observed more often in
animals that were weakly positive or negative by ELISA or IFA. Two
opposite shedding trends were thus apparent for the milk and
vaginal-fecal routes. Moreover, this study showed that a
non-negligible proportion of seronegative animals that delivered
normally could excrete _C. burnetii_.

[Byline: Elodie Rousset, Mustapha Berri, Benoit Durand, Philippe
Dufour, Myriam Prigent, Thibault Delcroix, Anne Touratier, and Annie Rodolakis]

